RBAC Policy for MicroStrategy Environment Deployment
Overview

This section describes the Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) requirements needed to deploy a MicroStrategy environment on OpenShift using Ansible automation and the MicroStrategy Operator.

Proper RBAC configuration ensures:

Secure access control

Successful environment provisioning

Avoidance of SCC and permission-related failures

Compliance with enterprise security standards

Why RBAC is Required

The MicroStrategy deployment workflow performs multiple operations across cluster and namespace levels.

Without proper RBAC:

MstrEnvironment CR creation fails

Service Mesh updates fail

Pods remain in Pending state

SCC (Security Context Constraint) errors occur

Deployment Operations Requiring RBAC

The following operations are executed during automation:

Step	Resource	Action
Login to cluster	OpenShift API	authenticate
Validate SMCP	servicemeshcontrolplanes	get
Validate SMMR	servicemeshmemberrolls	get
Add namespace to mesh	servicemeshmemberrolls	update
Create namespace	namespaces	create
Deploy MSTR environment	mstrenvironments	create
Create route	routes	create
Manage workloads	pods, deployments	create/update
Storage provisioning	PVC	create
Secrets creation	secrets	create
Backup jobs	jobs	create
Log collection	pods/log	get
Scaling workloads	deployments	patch
RBAC Design Approach

For enterprise environments, the recommended RBAC model includes:

ClusterRole → for cluster-level operations

ClusterRoleBinding → assign to FID user or AD group

Namespace isolation → per environment
